BEGIN_PGML
Convert the given set-builder notation into a number line graph and interval notation.

[`[$set_builder]`]

[_]{$gt}{1}

[@KeyboardInstructions('In interval notation:')@]**

[_]{$interval}{12}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
The set-builder notation tells us to graph all numbers less than or equal to [`[$a]\text{.}`] So the shading can start all the way to the left "at [`-\infty`]" and extend up to [`[$a]\text{.}`] There should be a bracket at [`[$a]`] to indicate that [`[$a]`] is included.

>> [@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>600)@]*  <<

And we read the number line from left to right, with the shading extending to [`-\infty`] and going all the way up to [`[$a]\text{,}`] including [`[$a]\text{.}`] So in interval notation, the interval is [`[$interval]\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

